# Vercel Web Analytics Implementation

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for this Next.js portfolio project following the latest official documentation from vercel.com/docs/analytics/quickstart.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` package using npm
- Added dependency to package.json
- Generated package-lock.json for consistent dependency resolution

### 2. Analytics Component Integration
**Modified:** `src/app/layout.tsx`
- Added import statement: `import { Analytics } from '@vercel/analytics/next';`
- Added `<Analytics />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after the children
- Follows Next.js App Router pattern as documented in official Vercel docs

## Implementation Details

The implementation follows the official Vercel Web Analytics quickstart guide for Next.js App Router:
- Fetched latest documentation to ensure up-to-date installation steps
- Identified the project uses Next.js 14.2.3 with App Router architecture
- Located the root layout file at `src/app/layout.tsx`
- Added Analytics component in the correct position (inside body, after children)
- Preserved all existing code structure, imports, and styling

## Verification

✅ Build completed successfully (`npm run build`)
- No TypeScript errors
- No compilation errors
- Production build optimized properly
- Analytics integration adds minimal overhead to bundle size

## Next Steps

To complete the setup and start tracking analytics:
1. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard for this project
2. Deploy the application to Vercel (`vercel deploy`)
3. Verify analytics are working by checking the browser's Network tab for requests to `/<unique-path>/view`
4. View analytics data in the Vercel dashboard after users visit the site

## Files Changed
- `package.json` - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- `package-lock.json` - New file with locked dependencies
- `src/app/layout.tsx` - Added Analytics import and component
